11What is vector database?

A vector database is a specialized database designed to store, index and search vector embeddings—numerical representations of data like text, images, audio, or video. These embeddings are usually generated by machine learning models and capture semantic meaning.
Vector databases are used by a wide range of industries and applications that rely on machine learning, AI, and unstructured data. Here are some key users and use cases:
________________________________________
🧠 AI & Machine Learning Teams
•	Use case: Store and retrieve embeddings from models like BERT, CLIP, or OpenAI embeddings.
•	Why: Enables fast similarity search and context retrieval for LLMs and other models.
________________________________________
🔍 Search Engines & Semantic Search
•	Use case: Improve search relevance by matching queries with semantically similar documents.
•	Why: Traditional keyword search misses context; vector search finds meaning-based matches.
________________________________________
🛍️ E-commerce & Recommendation Systems
•	Use case: Recommend products based on user behavior or item similarity.
•	Why: Vectors capture user preferences and product features better than categorical data.
________________________________________
📷 Media & Entertainment
•	Use case: Image, video, and audio similarity search.
•	Why: Vectors represent visual/audio features, enabling content-based retrieval.
________________________________________
🏥 Healthcare & Life Sciences
•	Use case: Analyze medical images, genomics data, or clinical notes.
•	Why: Embeddings help find similar cases or patterns in complex data.
________________________________________
🛡️ Cybersecurity
•	Use case: Anomaly detection in logs or network traffic.
•	Why: Vectors can represent behavior patterns, making it easier to spot outliers.
________________________________________
🧾 Finance & Legal
•	Use case: Document similarity, fraud detection, and contract analysis.
•	Why: Embeddings help match similar clauses, detect unusual transactions, etc.


