What is dimension?

In the context of vectors and embeddings, dimension refers to the number of values (or components) in a vector. Each value represents a feature or aspect of the data being encoded.
 

 

Why Does Dimension Matter?
•	Low dimensions (e.g., 50–100): Faster, but less expressive.
•	High dimensions (e.g., 512–1536): More accurate, but heavier to compute and store.

An embedding is a numerical representation of data (like text, images, or audio) in a high-dimensional vector space. It captures the semantic meaning or essential features of the input so that similar items are close together in that space.
________________________________________
✅ Key Points About Embeddings
•	What it is: A list of numbers (vector) that represents the input.
•	Why: Computers can’t understand raw text or images directly, so embeddings turn them into numbers that preserve meaning.
•	Dimension: The length of the vector (e.g., 512, 768, or 1536 values).
•	Similarity: Items with similar meaning have embeddings that are close together (measured by cosine similarity or Euclidean distance).
________________________________________
🔍 Example
Sentence:
"How do I reset my password?"
Embedding (simplified):
[0.12,−0.45,0.67,...,0.89] [
(Usually hundreds or thousands of dimensions.)
